á","1200–Male":"1200–Zesnulý","1220–1291":"1220–1291","1200–Female":"1200–Zesnulá","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","about 1200":"okolo 1200","1291":"1291","England":"Anglie","Devon, England":"Devon, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1200–":"omkring 1200–Afdød","1200–Male":"1200–Afdød","1220–1291":"1220–1291","1200–Female":"1200–Afdød","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","about 1200":"omkring 1200","1291":"1291","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"about 1200–":"circa 1200–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1220–1291":"1220–1291","1200–Female":"1200–Overleden","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","about 1200":"circa 1200","1291":"1291","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1200–":"about 1200–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1220–1291":"1220–1291","1200–Female":"1200–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","about 1200":"about 1200","1291":"1291","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":59,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Maud was born about 1200, in England. She had at least 1 son with William Crispyn."},"et":{"about 1200–":"umbes 1200–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1220–1291":"1220–1291","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1291":"1291","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1200–":"noin 1200–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1220–1291":"1220–1291","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","122